The ``force-free" magnetosphere of a Kerr black-hole in the axisymmetric steady-state possesses
two integral functions of the stream-function $\Psi$; the field-line angular-velocity (FLAV)
$\Omega_{\rm F} (\Psi)$, and the current-function $I(\Psi)$. For the zero-angular-momentum-observer's
FLAV, i.e., $\Omega_{F {\omega}}\equiv\Omega_{\rm F}-\omega$, the iso-rotation law breaks
down; $\Omega_{\rm F {\omega}}$ vanishes at the null-surface $\cal{S}_{\rm N}$ with $\omega=\Omega_{\rm
F}$, where $\omega$ is the frame-dragging angular-velocity, and this gives rise to a subsequent
breakdown of the force-free and freezing-in conditions at $\cal{S}_{\rm N}$, and the particle-velocity
and the electric-current must vanish at $\cal{S}_{\rm N}$. These impose strong constraints on
a possible gap to be constructed at $\cal{S}_{\rm N}$ between the force-free domains, $\cal{D}_{\rm
out}$ and $\cal{D}_{\rm in}$. Current circuits, $\cal{C}_{\rm out}$ and $\cal{C}_{\rm in}$,
must be closed in each domain, with EMFs $\cal{E}_{\rm out}$ and $\cal{E}_{\rm in}$, respectively,
oppositely directed at the inductive membrane $\cal{S}_{\rm N}$ and with resistances $I_{\rm
(out)}$ and $I_{\rm (in)}$ at the resistive membranes $\cal{S}_{{\rm ff}\infty}$ and $\cal{S}_{{\rm
ffH}}$. The particles pair-produced in $\cal{G}_{\rm N}$ must be ``zero-angular-momentum-particles",
which will be dense enough to pin down the poloidal field-lines ${\bf B}_p$ threading $\cal{G}_{\rm
N}$, to ensure magnetisation of $\cal{G}_{\rm N}$. The zero-angular-momentum-state of $\cal{G}_{\rm
N}$ makes it possible in $\cal{D}_{\rm in}$ that the outgoing-flux $I_{\rm (in)}$ of {\em positive}-angular-momentum
from the hole is equivalent to the ingoing-flux $I^{\rm (in)}$ of {\em negative}-angular-momentum
from $\cal{G}_{\rm N}$, i.e., $I_{\rm (in)}(\Psi)=-I^{\rm (in)}(\Psi)$. A twin-pulsar model
is proposed. 